snippet.textDisplay:
Not that it will be seen or cared about, but I have to say I think the motivation was the bigger factor.

15 minutes isn't a very long training session BUT from watching I honestly think either of them could have gotten it at least once in that time.

Ethan was absolutely right in saying Spencer wasn't motivated by the food and got bored, but at the end when he jumped around with him and grabbed the ball? Spencer was utterly focused. Had Ethan held a ball and had him work through some known tricks to establish the concept, throwing the ball could have been a great reward assuming Spencer is good at bringing it back. Play was far more interesting to him which explains him getting distracted by what looked, to him, like Mark and Chica wrestling.

Chica on the other hand is the cuddliest dog I have ever seen. It almost looks like at one point she starts taking the treats more to make Mark happy than because she wanted them. For that I think a focus on verbal and physical praise is really good for her but be aware, when the petting starts the listening stops. She is in happy heaven. Treats can still be used, but when Mark got really excited for her and she started doing zoomies? That is her high value reward.

Retaining a trick is all about repetition. You need multiple days or even weeks to establish that.

Training a concept quickly is very possible, just be aware the faster you train the faster they will forget. The key to quick training is a high value reward. For some it is a good treat, but for others it isn't.

My last piece that I think could have helped here is variety. If the dog isn't getting it, do things they know. If you are learning math and you get easy questions you know (2+2, 1x1, 5-0) then all of a sudden someone presents a formula that you don't understand? It is very easy to get frustrated. If you enter that new concept feeling good about your skills, you are more likely to invest in figuring it out. If that new concept is just thrust at you repeatedly, you are more likely to get frustrated and not care or perhaps even deliberately refuse to learn. Dogs get frustrated the same way. Try a new trick a few times then run them through what they know. Try again a few times then run them through what they know in a different order. Keep them engaged and remind them that they have learned before and they can get this.

I am by no means an expert and every dog is different, but hopefully this information can help someone. I have no dog training certifications and I don't show dogs I just come from a family of long term rescuers and have grown up working with dogs who had behavior problems. Dog training has been a part of my life for all of my life and I absolutely loved this video. Hopefully my thoughts on it can help someone in a frustrating spot of training or just entertain someone who is interested.

snippet.textDisplay: I am not a pro, but what i know is that you shouldn’t repeat the word over and over, only when the dog is doing it. When you do it over and over the dog wont know what action means bang. And when you try something like that, do it in parts then make it harder and harder so you don’t bore the dog. Start with just laying down, then on the side, and in the end all the way :)
